I took my grandparents and mom here on Christmas Eve, and they couldn't get enough. My great grandmother passed away about 25 years ago and did not pass on her recipes as her son married an Irish woman. I was too young to remember her meat sauce, but ever since, my grandmother has attempted to remake the sauce and has always been a bit disappointed with the result. Taking my grandparents here was the first time I've seen my grandpa finally find the same pasta sauce. As it turns out, that the family that owns this restaurant came from the same town in Italy as my grandpa did.  Being unbiased, I'd probably give this restaurant a 4/5 and plan to go back every so often, but now my grandparents are constantly asking to visit me in Chicago so we can come back. I personally didn't love the pasta. However, my veal was delightful and the owner was very kind to my family, so I will be back soon. I also enjoyed singing Jingle Bells with the rest of the restaurant.

A very not upscale restaurant in an upscale neighborhood selling old school Italian food.  At first glance you want to turn and leave because visually it has a look of one of those places that tries to hard to look unassuming...red checked table clothes, but then you realize that this place is not going for that look, this is the look.  Food is good and the portions are huge.  You can easily split a dish or take half home for a snack for the next day.  I prefer the baked pasta dishes as they seem to have more sauce that just the pasta and sauce.  The meatballs were nice and juicy and are a must with the baked pasta.  I really love their pizza bread and that in itself can be a meal.  It is topped with sliced Italian sausage.  While it is great, I don't recommend eating more than 2 slices, otherwise you will not be able to finish your meal.  Staff is nice.  Our bartender Felicia was the hardest working person in the joint, serving drinks and food at the bar and it appeared that she was also taking drinks to tables as well.  Not sure if he was the owner or host, but there was a silvered haired gentlemen behind the bar as well who was very cordial.  My only complaint would be the $9.50 for a glass of Prosecco...that is an upscale price and too much, in my opinion, for a neighborhood place.  But this is a place I can definitely visit again.

Went here on a Saturday night with my wife and ordered a bottle of wine. Cafe Lago was charging $35. I've had the wine before and it's a great bottle. Boom. I'm immediately excited for the great 2012 Cortena Malbec and pasta I'm about to experience.  The waiter brought us "the bottle we ordered" to the table OPENED. The bottle was filled  1/4 of the way up the neck. I give it a pass, thinking it may be 1/10,000 coincidence the bottle was full beyond normal capacity and also opened when we received it.  Sadly, this was me being nice. The wine tasted nothing like the Malbec we had ordered.  We were bait-and-switched with CHEAP WINE!!!  We didn't bother to stick around and eat because of the egregious handling, but I can safely say we won't eat here ever.
